&lt;?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>Blog – Nipun Pruthi</title><link>https://nipunpruthi.github.io/blog/</link><description>Software engineer</description><generator>Hugo 0.155.3</generator><language>en</language><lastBuildDate>Sat, 14 Feb 2026 06:55:49 +0000</lastBuildDate><atom:link href="https://nipunpruthi.github.io/blog/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>First steps with Hugo</title><link>https://nipunpruthi.github.io/blog/first-steps-with-hugo/</link><pubDate>Wed, 15 Jan 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://nipunpruthi.github.io/blog/first-steps-with-hugo/</guid><description>&lt;![CDATA[&amp;lt;p&amp;gt;Hugo is a fast static site generator. Here are a few things that make it pleasant to use.&amp;lt;/p&amp;gt;
&amp;lt;p&amp;gt;You write content in Markdown and keep structure in templates. The &amp;lt;code&amp;gt;hugo server&amp;lt;/code&amp;gt; live reload is quick, and building a full site takes a second or two even for hundreds of pages. That makes it a good fit for blogs, docs, and personal sites.&amp;lt;/p&amp;gt;]]&gt;</description></item><item><title>Simple CI/CD for static sites</title><link>https://nipunpruthi.github.io/blog/simple-cicd-for-static-sites/</link><pubDate>Wed, 08 Jan 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://nipunpruthi.github.io/blog/simple-cicd-for-static-sites/</guid><description>&lt;![CDATA[&amp;lt;p&amp;gt;For a static site on GitHub Pages, you can avoid committing build artifacts and let CI do the work.&amp;lt;/p&amp;gt;
&amp;lt;p&amp;gt;A single GitHub Actions workflow can checkout the repo, install Hugo, run &amp;lt;code&amp;gt;hugo --minify&amp;lt;/code&amp;gt;, and deploy the contents of &amp;lt;code&amp;gt;public/&amp;lt;/code&amp;gt; to the Pages branch. The &amp;lt;code&amp;gt;GITHUB_TOKEN&amp;lt;/code&amp;gt; is enough for push access when the workflow is in the same repo.&amp;lt;/p&amp;gt;]]&gt;</description></item><item><title>Why Markdown for content</title><link>https://nipunpruthi.github.io/blog/why-markdown-for-content/</link><pubDate>Fri, 20 Dec 2024 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://nipunpruthi.github.io/blog/why-markdown-for-content/</guid><description>&lt;![CDATA[&amp;lt;p&amp;gt;Markdown is a good default for writing content that ends up on the web.&amp;lt;/p&amp;gt;
&amp;lt;p&amp;gt;It’s readable as plain text, so you can edit it in any editor and keep it in version control. Formatting is minimal: headings, lists, links, code blocks. That keeps the focus on what you’re saying instead of layout tweaks.&amp;lt;/p&amp;gt;]]&gt;</description></item><item><title>Keeping a reading list</title><link>https://nipunpruthi.github.io/blog/keeping-a-reading-list/</link><pubDate>Thu, 05 Dec 2024 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://nipunpruthi.github.io/blog/keeping-a-reading-list/</guid><description>&lt;![CDATA[&amp;lt;p&amp;gt;A simple reading list helps me actually finish books and articles instead of losing them in tabs.&amp;lt;/p&amp;gt;
&amp;lt;p&amp;gt;I keep a single markdown file: title, author, status (reading / done), and a line or two of notes when I’m done. No fancy tool, just something I can grep and edit anywhere.&amp;lt;/p&amp;gt;]]&gt;</description></item></channel></rss>